## cp1 — Dockerfile restructure for Tier 2 (COMPLETE)

### Key finding: `puppeteer` is in `dependencies`

`apps/api/package.json` has `puppeteer: "^25.1.0"` in `dependencies` (not devDeps).
It must stay there — the render worker (same package source) needs it at runtime.
`PUPPETEER_SKIP_CHROMIUM_DOWNLOAD=true` in the API builder prevents Chrome download.
`pnpm deploy --prod` includes the puppeteer package (~5 MB) but no Chrome binary.
`puppeteer` is never loaded at runtime in the API (ReportCardRenderModule removed).

### `apps/api/Dockerfile` (rewrite)

**Builder stage:**
- Removed `RUN apt-get install unzip` — Chrome is never downloaded so the zip is
  never extracted; unzip not needed in the API builder.
- Added `ENV PUPPETEER_SKIP_CHROMIUM_DOWNLOAD=true` before `pnpm install`.
- After all three build steps: `RUN pnpm --filter @school-kit/api deploy --prod /app/api-deploy`.
  `pnpm deploy` creates a self-contained production directory:
  - Package files (dist/, src/, package.json) at root
  - `@school-kit/db` (with dist/ + generated/ Prisma client) and `@school-kit/types`
    (with dist/) copied into node_modules/@school-kit/
  - All third-party prod deps; devDeps (~2 GB) excluded

**Runtime stage:**
- Removed all Chromium OS libs (`libnss3`, `libatk*`, etc.) and `fonts-liberation`.
- `COPY --from=builder /app/api-deploy ./`
- `CMD ["node", "dist/main.js"]` — deploy dir root is /app, so dist/main.js is correct.
- No `PUPPETEER_CACHE_DIR` env needed.

Expected image: ~600 MB (from 3.41 GB).

### `apps/api/Dockerfile.render` (NEW)

Builder stage: identical to the old API Dockerfile (Chrome downloads to
`/app/.cache/puppeteer`; `unzip` installed). After builds:
```
RUN pnpm --filter @school-kit/api deploy --prod /app/render-deploy
RUN cp -r /app/.cache /app/render-deploy/.cache
```
Chrome lands at `/app/render-deploy/.cache/puppeteer/chrome/...` — the same relative
path the `PUPPETEER_CACHE_DIR` env points at in the runtime stage.

Runtime stage: all Chromium OS libs present. `COPY --from=builder /app/render-deploy ./`.
`ENV PUPPETEER_CACHE_DIR=/app/.cache/puppeteer`. `CMD ["node", "dist/main-render-worker.js"]`.

### `apps/api/src/app.module.ts`

Removed `ReportCardRenderModule` import and its entry in the imports array.
`ReportCardsModule` stays — the API still owns the HTTP `/report-cards` endpoints
and enqueues BullMQ render jobs.

### `apps/api/src/render-worker.module.ts` (NEW)

Root module for `school-kit-render-worker`. Inline `WorkerHealthController`:
```typescript
@Controller()
class WorkerHealthController {
  @Get("health")
  health(): { status: string } { return { status: "ok" }; }
}
```
Imports: `ConfigModule` (global), `QueueModule` (BullMQ+Redis), `StorageModule`
(R2 upload), `ReportCardsModule` (ReportCardService + queue token), `ReportCardRenderModule`
(BrowserPool + RenderService + Processor).

`ReportCardsModule` transitively imports `AuthModule` and `AssessmentModule`. Their
controllers load but are never routed (no global prefix, no HTTP routes wired to them).
NestJS ignores unrouted controllers in an HTTP app. ~20-30 MB extra RSS, acceptable.

### `apps/api/src/main-render-worker.ts` (NEW)

```typescript
const app = await NestFactory.create(RenderWorkerModule, {
  logger: ["error", "warn", "log"],
});
app.enableShutdownHooks();
await app.listen(Number(process.env.RENDER_WORKER_PORT ?? 4001));
```

`enableShutdownHooks()` is load-bearing: Fly sends SIGTERM on scale-to-zero and
deploys; without it a mid-render SIGTERM leaves `pdfStatus` stuck at PENDING.

### `report-card-workflow.service.ts` — `release()` wake call

Changed `return withTenant(...)` to `const result: ReportCardTransitionResultDto = await withTenant(...)`.
The explicit type annotation is required because the inferred type narrows to
`{ status: string; cardCount: number }` when assigned to a `const`, which is not
assignable to `ReportCardTransitionResultDto` (expects `status: ReportCardStatusDto`).

After the tx commits:
```typescript
const renderWorkerUrl = process.env.RENDER_WORKER_URL;
if (renderWorkerUrl) {
  fetch(`${renderWorkerUrl}/health`).catch(() => {});
}
```
Fire-and-forget. Errors are swallowed — a failed wake doesn't fail the release;
jobs wait in the BullMQ queue until the render worker is manually started or
the next scheduled boot.

